---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const rating = 4;
const stars = '★'.repeat(rating) + '☆'.repeat(5 - rating);
---

<Base title="Andaz Peninsula Papagayo — Stay Nivas" description="A review of Andaz Costa Rica Resort at Peninsula Papagayo, through the lens of feeling, presence, and craft.">
  <article class="review">
    <!-- Hero Image -->
    <div class="review-hero">
      <img src="/images/andaz-papagayo/hero.jpg" alt="View of Culebra Bay from the Andaz Papagayo through tropical foliage" />
    </div>

    <div class="container">
      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="review-header">
        <p class="review-location">Guanacaste, Costa Rica</p>
        <h1>Andaz Peninsula Papagayo</h1>
        <p class="review-subtitle">Where the jungle decides what kind of guest you'll be</p>
        <div class="review-meta-bar">
          <span class="review-rating" aria-label={`${rating} out of 5 stars`}>{stars}</span>
          <span class="review-date">March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </header>

      <!-- Metadata -->
      <aside class="review-metadata">
        <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Property</span> Andaz Costa Rica Resort at Peninsula Papagayo</div>
        <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Location</span> Peninsula Papagayo, Guanacaste, Costa Rica</div>
        <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Room</span> Ocean View Suite</div>
        <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Traveled</span> Family</div>
        <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Nights</span> 4</div>
        <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Would Return</span> Yes</div>
      </aside>

      <!-- Body -->
      <div class="review-body">
        <h2>Arrival</h2>
        <p>
          You don't arrive at the Andaz so much as descend into it. The drive through Peninsula Papagayo is a slow unwinding. Dry tropical forest on both sides, the occasional howler monkey staking a territorial claim from somewhere above, and then the road opens to an arrival pavilion that has no walls. Just wood, stone, and the Pacific filling the frame where a lobby wall should be.
        </p>
        <p>
          The check-in happens standing up, with a cold towel and a tamarind juice that's sharp enough to snap you out of whatever travel fog you carried in. Nobody rushes you. Nobody hands you a keycard with corporate efficiency. Someone walks you to your room through a path that smells like frangipani and warm earth.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is the first thing the Andaz gets right: it doesn't announce itself. It lets the place do that.
        </p>

        <figure class="review-image">
          <img src="/images/andaz-papagayo/lobby.jpg" alt="Open-air lobby overlooking the Pacific at Andaz Papagayo" />
          <figcaption>The open-air lobby. No walls, no pretension, just the bay.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>The Space</h2>
        <p>
          The rooms are built into the hillside, and the designers made one excellent choice that defines the entire experience: every room faces the water. Not sideways. Not if you crane from the balcony. The bed faces the window, the window faces the bay, and the first thing you see each morning is the Pacific doing whatever the Pacific does that day.
        </p>
        <p>
          The rain shower opens onto a semi-outdoor space. There's a bird's nest-inspired balcony that sounds gimmicky in a brochure but works in practice. You sit in it with coffee and realize you haven't checked your phone in two hours. That's the test, and this room passes it.
        </p>
        <p>
          Materials throughout are warm and local. Driftwood, volcanic stone, fabrics in muted earth tones. Nothing screams for attention. The minibar is complimentary, a small Andaz signature that signals: we're not going to nickel-and-dime you. It's a tiny thing, but it changes the psychology of the stay.
        </p>

        <figure class="review-image">
          <img src="/images/andaz-papagayo/room.jpg" alt="Ocean-facing suite with natural materials and warm tones" />
          <figcaption>The room does one thing perfectly: it points you at the water and gets out of the way.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>Nourishment</h2>
        <p>
          Breakfast at the Andaz Beach House is barefoot and unhurried. The buffet is generous but not performative. Fresh tropical fruit that actually tastes like fruit, not the decorative kind you get at most resort spreads. The gallo pinto is good. The eggs are made to order by someone who seems to care whether you want them runny.
        </p>
        <p>
          Ostra, the signature seafood restaurant, is where the food program shows its ambition. A ceviche with local corvina and coconut leche de tigre that was the best single bite of the trip. The setting helps: you're eating on a terrace above the bay, and the menu feels connected to where you are rather than imported from a corporate playbook.
        </p>
        <p>
          If there's a weakness, it's lunch. The pool bar menu leans safe and international in a way that feels like a missed opportunity. This close to the ocean, in this country, I wanted more risk. More ceviche, more casados, less Caesar salad.
        </p>

        <h2>The People</h2>
        <p>
          Costa Rican hospitality has a specific warmth to it. Not the studied precision of Japanese service or the choreographed charm of European luxury. It's more like being welcomed into someone's family compound, except the compound has an infinity pool and a spa.
        </p>
        <p>
          The staff at the Andaz lean into this. By day two, the woman at breakfast knew we wanted our coffee before we sat down. The pool attendant learned our son's name and waved at him every morning like a neighbor. These aren't trained behaviors. They're the real thing, or close enough that I couldn't tell the difference.
        </p>
        <p>
          One moment stood out: our son had a meltdown at dinner (he's two, it happens), and instead of the polite grimace you get at most fine dining restaurants, our server brought out a small toy monkey and set it on the table without a word. No fuss, no performance. Just someone reading a room and responding with kindness.
        </p>

        <figure class="review-image">
          <img src="/images/andaz-papagayo/beach.jpg" alt="Quiet morning on the resort's private beach with calm Pacific waters" />
          <figcaption>Early morning, before the chairs fill up. This is when the beach belongs to you.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>Stillness</h2>
        <p>
          On the third morning, I woke up before everyone else and walked down to the beach. The water in Culebra Bay at 6am is absurdly still. A pelican dove, caught something, and flew off. That was the entire event. I sat there for twenty minutes and felt something I rarely feel at hotels: I felt held by the place without being managed by it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Andaz's greatest quality is restraint. It doesn't fill your schedule with activities and excursions and "curated experiences." There's a beautiful pool. There are two beaches. There's a spa that smells like lemongrass. And there's the forest, which is alive in a way that makes the property feel like a guest in the jungle rather than the other way around.
        </p>
        <p>
          A howler monkey woke us at 5am every single morning. It should have been annoying. It wasn't. It was the property's unofficial alarm clock, a reminder that you're on someone else's schedule here. And that someone is the forest.
        </p>

        <h2>Would You Return?</h2>
        <p>
          Yes. The Andaz Papagayo is a place that knows what it is. It's not the most luxurious resort on the peninsula (Four Seasons has it beat on pure polish), and the lunch menu and some of the common areas show the stretch marks of being a 170-room property trying to feel intimate. But what it offers is rarer than luxury: a genuine sense of place.
        </p>
        <p>
          This property is for families who want beauty without fussiness, couples who want romance without performance, and anyone who's ever walked into a gorgeous hotel and felt nothing. The Andaz makes you feel something. That's the whole job, and it does it well.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Back -->
      <div class="review-back">
        <a href="/">&larr; All Reviews</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .review-hero {
    width: 100%;
    max-height: 70vh;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .review-hero img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 70vh;
    object-fit: cover;
  }

  .review-header {
    padding: 3rem 0 2rem;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .review-location {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    color: var(--color-slate);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .review-header h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: 0.25em;
  }

  .review-subtitle {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--color-slate);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .review-meta-bar {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 2rem;
    align-items: center;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }

  .review-rating {
    color: var(--color-saffron);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  }

  .review-date {
    color: var(--color-slate);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* Metadata sidebar */
  .review-metadata {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0 auto 3rem;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    background: rgba(212, 197, 169, 0.15);
    border-radius: 4px;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 0.75rem 2rem;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }

  .meta-label {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--color-slate);
    margin-bottom: 0.15em;
  }

  /* Body */
  .review-body {
    max-width: 650px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .review-body h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    margin: 3rem 0 1rem;
    color: var(--color-charcoal);
  }

  .review-body h2:first-child {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .review-body p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .review-image {
    margin: 2.5rem -2rem;
  }

  .review-image img {
    width: calc(100% + 4rem);
    max-width: none;
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 10;
    object-fit: cover;
  }

  .review-image figcaption {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--color-slate);
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    font-style: italic;
    padding: 0 2rem;
  }

  .review-back {
    max-width: 650px;
    margin: 4rem auto 0;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-warm-sand);
  }

  .review-back a {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .review-metadata {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .review-image {
      margin: 2rem -1.5rem;
    }

    .review-image img {
      width: calc(100% + 3rem);
    }

    .review-image figcaption {
      padding: 0 1.5rem;
    }
  }
</style>
